\begin_layout Standard
In order to obtain a mass profile for each halo in funcion of the radius,
 the center of each halo must be calculated.
 However the center of mass will not give an accurate position for the center
 because some haloes are highly irregular, is more convenient to take the
 gravitational potential for each particle
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi\left(\boldsymbol{r}_{n}\right)=-\sum_{j\neq i}\frac{1}{\left\Vert \boldsymbol{r}_{n}-\boldsymbol{r}_{j}\right\Vert }
\]

\end_inset

Take 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}_{0}=\min\left(\phi\left(\boldsymbol{r}_{n}\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 as the center then define new coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}_{n}^{\prime}=\boldsymbol{r}_{0}-\boldsymbol{r}_{n}$
\end_inset

, this 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}_{0}$
\end_inset

 will be in the most relevant region for the dynamics of each halo.
 Organizing the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \boldsymbol{r}_{n}^{\prime}\right\} $
\end_inset

 in crescent order, the accumulated mass for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}_{n}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 will be 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{n}=nm$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

