\begin_layout Standard
The last part of the process consists in fitting the NFW mass profile to
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{n}$
\end_inset

 data using the Metropolis-Hastings algorithm to sample the Likelihood 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal L}\left(\rho_{0},r_{s}\right)=\exp\left(-\frac{1}{2}\chi^{2}\left(\rho_{0},r_{s}\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\chi^{2}\left(\rho_{0},r_{s}\right)=\sum\limits _{n}\left|m_{n}-m\left(r_{n}^{\prime},\rho_{0},r_{s}\right)\right|^{2}
\]

\end_inset

And taking the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{s}$
\end_inset

 where the Likelihood is maximum.
 After this the concentration 
\begin_inset Formula $c=r_{vir}/r_{s}$
\end_inset

 is computed for each halo.
 Finally we compare this results with the results obtaned by BDM, since
 the number of halos obtained by FOF and BDM is different, each BDM halo
 gets related with the nearest halo in FOF.
 We compute two concentrations, one where the overdensity limit is 
\begin_inset Formula $360\rho_{back}$
\end_inset

 (like in BDMV) an other where the overdensity limit is 
\begin_inset Formula $740\rho_{back}$
\end_inset

 (like in BDMW).
\end_layout

